This study attempts to estimate potential gains in life expectancy in 1984 
through partial and complete elimination of infectious and parasitic diseases 
among Kuwaiti nationals. For deriving these estimates, a multiple decrement life 
table approach was applied. The results of the study show that complete 
elimination of infectious and parasitic disease mortality would further add 0.45 
years to the life expectancy at birth of Kuwaiti males and 0.54 yr to that of 
Kuwaiti females. A partial reduction by 50% would result in gains of just 
one-half of the years gained through complete elimination of these causes. Also, 
as partial reduction is increased from 10% to 90%, the gains in life expectancy 
at birth would go up from 0.04 yr to 0.40 yr in the case of Kuwaiti males and 
0.06 to 0.48 yr for Kuwaiti females.

